			<h5>Low Discrepancy Samplers</h5>
			
			<p>When using random sampling, a large number of samples can be required before a uniform distribution over the sample space is achieved. As a result, a relatively 
			large number of samples are required to reduce noise when using random sampling. A more efficient strategy is to use low discrepancy sampling sequences which 
			ensure a good distribution of samples over the sample space. One of the simplest such sequences is the van der Corput sequence which is a low discrepancy sequence
			over a single dimension. Intalgio uses two dimensional Halton (a higher dimensional generalization of the van der Corput sequence) and the 
			Hammersely sequences when sampling. The Hammersely sequence is used in most situations such as sampling luminaries. The Halton sequence is used specifically 
			for generating photon emission directs as it is capable of generating samples even when the total number of required samples is unknown initially.</p>
			
			</div>
			
